{"title_page": "Dark Waters (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 American legal thriller film directed by Todd Haynes}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dark Waters\n| image          = Dark Waters poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Todd Haynes]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n* [[Christine Vachon]]\n* Pamela Koffler\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Mario Correa\n* [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|\"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\"|[[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Ruffalo\n* [[Anne Hathaway]]\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Bill Camp]]\n* [[Victor Garber]]\n* [[Mare Winningham]]\n* [[Bill Pullman]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[Marcelo Zarvos]]\n| cinematography = [[Edward Lachman]]\n| editing        = [[Affonso Gon\u00e7alves]]\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Participant (company)|Participant]]\n* [[Killer Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amctheatres.com/movies/dark-waters-61544 |title=Dark Waters |publisher=[[AMC Theatres]] |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million\n| gross          = $21 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkwaters.htm |title=Dark Waters (2019) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]. [[IMDb]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dark Waters''''' is a 2019 American [[legal thriller]] film directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and written by Mario Correa and [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]. The story dramatizes [[Robert Bilott]]'s case against the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]] after they contaminated a town with unregulated chemicals. It stars [[Mark Ruffalo]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]].\n\nThe film is based on the 2016 ''[[The New York Times Magazine|New York Times Magazine]]'' article \"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\" by [[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rich|first=Nathaniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|title=The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare|date=January 6, 2016|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|access-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143157/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|issn=0362-4331|authorlink=Nathaniel Rich (novelist)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143206/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Parts of the story were also reported by Mariah Blake, whose 2015 article \"Welcome to Beautiful Parkersburg, West Virginia\" was a National Magazine Award finalist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|title=American Society of Magazine Editors Unveils Finalists for 2016 National Magazine Awards|last=Steigrad|first=Alexandra|date=January 14, 2016|website=WWD|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143132/https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> and Sharon Lerner, whose series \"Bad Chemistry\" ran in ''[[The Intercept]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|title=Bad Chemistry|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=October 24, 2019|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402142717/https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2015/08/11/dupont-chemistry-deception/|title=The Teflon Toxin: DuPont and the Chemistry of Deception|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=August 11, 2015|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://perma.cc/89PM-XBGW|archive-date=February 25, 2015|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Bilott also wrote a memoir, ''Exposure'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/exposurepoisoned0000bilo|title=Exposure: poisoned water, corporate greed, and one lawyer's twenty-year battle against DuPont |last=Bilott|first=Robert|date=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Atria Books |via=The Internet Archive}}</ref> detailing his 20-year legal battle against DuPont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|title=Lawyer who took on DuPont has book coming out|date=July 10, 2019|website=Associated Press News|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143821/https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n''Dark Waters'' had a limited theatrical release on November 22, 2019, by [[Focus Features]], and went wide on December 6, 2019. The film received positive reviews from critics and has grossed $21 million.\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Robert Bilott]] is a corporate defense lawyer from [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] working for law firm [[Taft Stettinius & Hollister]]. Farmer Wilbur Tennant, who knows Robert's grandmother, asks Robert to investigate a number of unexplained deaths in [[Parkersburg, West Virginia]]. Tennant connects the deaths to the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]], and gives Robert a large case of videotapes.\n\nRobert visits the Tennants' farm, where he learns that 190 cattle have died with unusual medical conditions such as bloated organs, blackened teeth, and tumors. DuPont attorney Phil Donnelly tells him he is not aware of the case but will help out in any way he can. Robert files a small suit so he can gain information through [[legal discovery]] of the chemicals dumped on the site. When he finds nothing useful in the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] report, he realizes the chemicals might not be regulated by the EPA.\n\nRobert confronts Phil at an industry event, leading to an angry exchange. DuPont sends Robert hundreds of boxes, hoping to bury the evidence. Robert finds numerous references to PFOA, a chemical with no references in any medical textbook. In the middle of the night, Robert's pregnant wife Sarah finds him tearing the carpet off the floors and going through their pans. He has discovered that PFOA is [[perfluorooctanoic acid]], used to manufacture [[Teflon]] and used in American homes for nonstick pans. PFAS are commonly found in every American household, and in products as diverse as non- stick cookware, stain resistant furniture and carpets, wrinkle free and water repellant clothing, cosmetics, lubricants, paint, pizza boxes, popcorn bags, and many other everyday products. <ref>https://casaweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/National-PFAS-Receivers-Factsheet.pdf</ref> DuPont has been running tests of the effect of PFOA for decades, finding that it causes cancer and birth defects, but did not make the findings public. They dumped hundreds of gallons of toxic sludge upriver from Tennant's farm. PFOA and similar compounds are [[Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances#Forever chemicals|forever chemicals]], chemicals that do not leave the blood stream [[Bioaccumulation|and slowly accumulate]].\n\nTennant has been shunned by the community for suing their biggest employer, and he and his wife both have cancer. Robert encourages him to accept DuPont's settlement, but Tennant refuses, wanting justice. He tells Robert he and his wife both have cancer. Robert sends the DuPont evidence to the EPA and Department of Justice, among others. The EPA fines DuPont $16.5 million.\n\nRobert, however, is not satisfied; he realizes that the residents of Parkersburg will suffer the effects of the PFOA for the rest of their lives. He seeks [[Monitoring (medicine)|medical monitoring]] for all residents of Parkersburg in one large [[Class action|class-action lawsuit]]. However, DuPont sends a letter notifying residents of the presence of PFOA, thus starting the [[statute of limitations]] and giving any further action only a month to begin.\n\nSince PFOA is not regulated, Robert's team argues that the corporation is liable, as the amount in the water was higher than the one part per billion deemed safe by DuPont's internal documents. In court, DuPont claims their later study found that 150 parts per billion is safe. The locals protest and the story becomes national news. DuPont agrees to settle for $70 million. As DuPont is only required to carry out medical monitoring if scientists prove that PFOA causes the ailments, an independent scientific review is set up. To get data for it, DuPont tells the locals they can get their settlement money after donating blood. Nearly 70,000 people donate to the study. PFOA and PFOS are found in every American person\u2019s blood stream in the parts per billion range, though those concentrations have decreased by 70% for PFOA and 84% for PFOS between 1999 and 2014, which coincides with the end of the production and phase out of PFOA and PFOS in the US2. <ref>https://casaweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/National-PFAS-Receivers-Factsheet.pdf</ref>\n \n\nSeven years pass with no result from the study. Tennant dies and Robert becomes destitute following several pay cuts, straining his marriage. When Tom tells him he needs to take another pay cut, Robert collapses, shaking. Doctors tell Sarah he suffered an [[ischemia]], brought on by stress. Sarah tells Tom to stop making Robert feel like a failure, since he is doing something for people who need help.\n\nThe scientific review contacts Robert and tells him that PFOA causes multiple cancers and other diseases. At dinner with his family, Robert is informed that DuPont is reneging on the entire agreement. Robert decides to take each defendant's case to DuPont, one at a time. He wins the first three multimillion-dollar settlements against DuPont, and DuPont settles the class action for $671 million.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as [[Robert Bilott]]\n* [[Anne Hathaway]] as Sarah Bilott\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Tom Terp\n* [[Bill Camp]] as Wilbur Tennant \n* [[Victor Garber]] as Phil Donnelly\n* [[Mare Winningham]] as Darlene Kiger\n* [[Bill Pullman]] as Harry Deitzler\n* [[William Jackson Harper]] as James Ross\n* [[Louisa Krause]] as Karla\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn September 21, 2018, it was announced that [[Todd Haynes]] would direct the film, then titled ''Dry Run'', from a script by [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], which would be produced by [[Participant (company)|Participant Media]] along with [[Mark Ruffalo]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|title='Carol' Helmer Todd Haynes To Direct 'Dry Run' Drama For Participant Media|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144115/https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> In November 2018, Ruffalo was officially set to star in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|title=Mark Ruffalo To Star In Participant Media's Todd Haynes Pic About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=November 9, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144302/https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Christine Vachon]] and Pamela Koffler producing under their [[Killer Films]] banner.<ref name=\"MoreCast\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144355/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] began on January 14, 2019, in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"MoreCast\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|title=Shooting for film starring Mark Ruffalo, Anne Hathaway begins in Hamilton Monday|last=\"WKRC\"|date=January 11, 2019|website=Local12.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144422/https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released in limited theatres on November 22, 2019, before going wide on December 6, 2019.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|title=\u2018Dark Waters\u2019 Leads Tepid Arthouse Openers at Crowded Box Office|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=November 27, 2019|website=[[Indiewire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144435/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Dark Waters'' grossed $11.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $9.9 million in other countries, for a worldwide total of $21 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nIn its opening weekend the film made $102,656 from four theaters, a per-venue average of $25,651.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> It expanded to 94 theaters the following weekend, making $630,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|title='Harriet,' 'Jojo Rabbit,' and 'Parasite' Reap Holiday Box Office Bounty|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=December 1, 2019|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144741/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref> The film went wide in its third weekend of release, making $4.1 million from 2,012 theaters, and then made $1.9 million in its fourth weekend.<ref name=\"expand\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|title=\u2018Frozen 2\u2019 Leads Dreary December Weekend With $34M+, \u2018Playmobil\u2019 Plunges To $670K \u2013 Sunday Update|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 8, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144822/https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|title=\u2018Jumanji: The Next Level\u2019 Advancing To $51M+ Opening; \u2018Richard Jewell\u2019 & \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 Earn Lumps Of Coal|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 15, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144821/https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 90% based on 197 reviews, with an average rating of 7.3/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Dark Waters'' powerfully relays a real-life tale of infuriating malfeasance, honoring the victims and laying blame squarely at the feet of the perpetrators.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019/|title=Dark Waters (2019)|date=December 6, 2019|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144827/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 72 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|title=Dark Waters Reviews|date=November 22, 2019|website=Metacritic|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145211/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars, with 60% saying they would definitely recommend it to a friend.<ref name=expand/>\n\n=== Economic response ===\nThe DowDuPont breakup earlier in the year spun off a new DuPont company that continued to lose value throughout the second half of 2019 as investors grew concerned about the potential liabilities related to the old DuPont's fluoropolymer products. When ''Dark Waters'' was released on November 12, DuPont's stock price dropped even further by 7.15 points from 72.18 to 65.03. While the portfolio is now a part of [[Chemours]] and the companies settled the public health lawsuits referenced in the film, Chemours sued DuPont, alleging that the former parent company saddled it with onerous liabilities when it failed to prepare financial projections in good faith. Chemours estimated that it would need to pay over $200 million to address environmental damages in North Carolina caused by another PFAS manufacturing facility in that region. (The prior settlement in both West Virginia and Ohio cost $671 million, which was split between the two companies.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|title=Here's Why DuPont Fell 40.5% in 2019|last=Chatsko|first=Maxx|date=January 9, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145208/https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuPont CEO Marc Doyle, executives, and investors argued in internal statements that much of the movie was not based in fact and DuPont was misconstrued to fit the role of the enemy. According to Doyle, limited public statements were made because \u201cin a situation like this, it just doesn\u2019t do you much good to fight it out in the public eye. That would just drive more and more attention to it.\u201d Executive chairman Ed Breen wouldn\u2019t comment on whether DuPont would take legal action in response to the movie, but he did tell investors, \u201cObviously, we have a lot of legal folks [that] have been looking at this.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|title=DuPont execs react to villain role in \u2018Dark Waters\u2019 film|last=Eichmann|first=Mark|date=November 1, 2019|website=whyy.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145229/https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Many of the executives with whom this movie draws fault still work, or recently worked at DuPont. 3M saw little to no change in its stock price the day of the film's release, but it was already experiencing a \"difficult year\" from \"potential liabilities due to possible litigation over previous production of PFAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|title=Is 3M Stock a Buy for 2020? The industrial giant had a very difficult 2019, but is it set for a turnaround in the coming year?|last=Samaha|first=Lee|date=December 18, 2019|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145533/https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> 3M's stock price closed at 256.01 on January 28, 2018, and by December 1, 2019, it had fallen to 168.27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|title=News & Analysis: 3M|last=Nyitray|first=Brent|date=April 1, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145639/https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Satellite Awards]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[24th Satellite Awards|December 19, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor, Drama]]\n| [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|title=24th Satellite Awards nominations|date=2019|website=pressacademy.com|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145910/https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Mario Correa, [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], Nathaniel Rich\n| {{nom}}\n |-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cinema for Peace]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala|February 23, 2020\n| Award for Justice 2020\n| ''Dark Waters''\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n|-\n| International Green Film Award 2020\n| ''Dark Waters''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Perfluorinated alkylated substances]] (PFAS)\n* [[Timeline of events related to per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)]]\n* ''[[The Devil We Know]]'' (2018 investigative documentary)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Todd Haynes}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2010s legal films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films about lawyers]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Todd Haynes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Christine Vachon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Films set in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2000]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2004]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2009]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2010]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2011]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Killer Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 American legal thriller film directed by Todd Haynes}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dark Waters\n| image          = Dark Waters poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Todd Haynes]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n* [[Christine Vachon]]\n* Pamela Koffler\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Mario Correa\n* [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|\"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\"|[[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Ruffalo\n* [[Anne Hathaway]]\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Bill Camp]]\n* [[Victor Garber]]\n* [[Mare Winningham]]\n* [[Bill Pullman]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[Marcelo Zarvos]]\n| cinematography = [[Edward Lachman]]\n| editing        = [[Affonso Gon\u00e7alves]]\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Participant (company)|Participant]]\n* [[Killer Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amctheatres.com/movies/dark-waters-61544 |title=Dark Waters |publisher=[[AMC Theatres]] |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million\n| gross          = $21 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkwaters.htm |title=Dark Waters (2019) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]. [[IMDb]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dark Waters''''' is a 2019 American [[legal thriller]] film directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and written by Mario Correa and [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]. The story dramatizes [[Robert Bilott]]'s case against the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]] after they contaminated a town with unregulated chemicals. It stars [[Mark Ruffalo]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]].\n\nThe film is based on the 2016 ''[[The New York Times Magazine|New York Times Magazine]]'' article \"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\" by [[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rich|first=Nathaniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|title=The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare|date=January 6, 2016|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|access-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143157/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|issn=0362-4331|authorlink=Nathaniel Rich (novelist)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143206/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Parts of the story were also reported by Mariah Blake, whose 2015 article \"Welcome to Beautiful Parkersburg, West Virginia\" was a National Magazine Award finalist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|title=American Society of Magazine Editors Unveils Finalists for 2016 National Magazine Awards|last=Steigrad|first=Alexandra|date=January 14, 2016|website=WWD|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143132/https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> and Sharon Lerner, whose series \"Bad Chemistry\" ran in ''[[The Intercept]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|title=Bad Chemistry|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=October 24, 2019|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402142717/https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2015/08/11/dupont-chemistry-deception/|title=The Teflon Toxin: DuPont and the Chemistry of Deception|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=August 11, 2015|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://perma.cc/89PM-XBGW|archive-date=February 25, 2015|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Bilott also wrote a memoir, ''Exposure'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/exposurepoisoned0000bilo|title=Exposure: poisoned water, corporate greed, and one lawyer's twenty-year battle against DuPont |last=Bilott|first=Robert|date=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Atria Books |via=The Internet Archive}}</ref> detailing his 20-year legal battle against DuPont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|title=Lawyer who took on DuPont has book coming out|date=July 10, 2019|website=Associated Press News|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143821/https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n''Dark Waters'' had a limited theatrical release on November 22, 2019, by [[Focus Features]], and went wide on December 6, 2019. The film received positive reviews from critics and has grossed $21 million.\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Robert Bilott]] is a corporate defense lawyer from [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] working for law firm [[Taft Stettinius & Hollister]]. Farmer Wilbur Tennant, who knows Robert's grandmother, asks Robert to investigate a number of unexplained deaths in [[Parkersburg, West Virginia]]. Tennant connects the deaths to the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]], and gives Robert a large case of videotapes.\n\nRobert visits the Tennants' farm, where he learns that 190 cattle have died with unusual medical conditions such as bloated organs, blackened teeth, and tumors. DuPont attorney Phil Donnelly tells him he is not aware of the case but will help out in any way he can. Robert files a small suit so he can gain information through [[legal discovery]] of the chemicals dumped on the site. When he finds nothing useful in the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] report, he realizes the chemicals might not be regulated by the EPA.\n\nRobert confronts Phil at an industry event, leading to an angry exchange. DuPont sends Robert hundreds of boxes, hoping to bury the evidence. Robert finds numerous references to PFOA, a chemical with no references in any medical textbook. In the middle of the night, Robert's pregnant wife Sarah finds him tearing the carpet off the floors and going through their pans. He has discovered that PFOA is [[perfluorooctanoic acid]], used to manufacture [[Teflon]] and used in American homes for nonstick pans. PFAS are commonly found in every American household, and in products as diverse as non- stick cookware, stain resistant furniture and carpets, wrinkle free and water repellant clothing, cosmetics, lubricants, paint, pizza boxes, popcorn bags, and many other everyday products. <ref>https://casaweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/National-PFAS-Receivers-Factsheet.pdf</ref> DuPont has been running tests of the effect of PFOA for decades, finding that it causes cancer and birth defects, but did not make the findings public. They dumped hundreds of gallons of toxic sludge upriver from Tennant's farm. PFOA and similar compounds are [[Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances#Forever chemicals|forever chemicals]], chemicals that do not leave the blood stream [[Bioaccumulation|and slowly accumulate]].\n\nTennant has been shunned by the community for suing their biggest employer, and he and his wife both have cancer. Robert encourages him to accept DuPont's settlement, but Tennant refuses, wanting justice. He tells Robert he and his wife both have cancer. Robert sends the DuPont evidence to the EPA and Department of Justice, among others. The EPA fines DuPont $16.5 million.\n\nRobert, however, is not satisfied; he realizes that the residents of Parkersburg will suffer the effects of the PFOA for the rest of their lives. He seeks [[Monitoring (medicine)|medical monitoring]] for all residents of Parkersburg in one large [[Class action|class-action lawsuit]]. However, DuPont sends a letter notifying residents of the presence of PFOA, thus starting the [[statute of limitations]] and giving any further action only a month to begin.\n\nSince PFOA is not regulated, Robert's team argues that the corporation is liable, as the amount in the water was higher than the one part per billion deemed safe by DuPont's internal documents. In court, DuPont claims their later study found that 150 parts per billion is safe. The locals protest and the story becomes national news. DuPont agrees to settle for $70 million. As DuPont is only required to carry out medical monitoring if scientists prove that PFOA causes the ailments, an independent scientific review is set up. To get data for it, DuPont tells the locals they can get their settlement money after donating blood. Nearly 70,000 people donate to the study.\n\nSeven years pass with no result from the study. Tennant dies and Robert becomes destitute following several pay cuts, straining his marriage. When Tom tells him he needs to take another pay cut, Robert collapses, shaking. Doctors tell Sarah he suffered an [[ischemia]], brought on by stress. Sarah tells Tom to stop making Robert feel like a failure, since he is doing something for people who need help.\n\nThe scientific review contacts Robert and tells him that PFOA causes multiple cancers and other diseases. At dinner with his family, Robert is informed that DuPont is reneging on the entire agreement. Robert decides to take each defendant's case to DuPont, one at a time. He wins the first three multimillion-dollar settlements against DuPont, and DuPont settles the class action for $671 million.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as [[Robert Bilott]]\n* [[Anne Hathaway]] as Sarah Bilott\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Tom Terp\n* [[Bill Camp]] as Wilbur Tennant \n* [[Victor Garber]] as Phil Donnelly\n* [[Mare Winningham]] as Darlene Kiger\n* [[Bill Pullman]] as Harry Deitzler\n* [[William Jackson Harper]] as James Ross\n* [[Louisa Krause]] as Karla\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn September 21, 2018, it was announced that [[Todd Haynes]] would direct the film, then titled ''Dry Run'', from a script by [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], which would be produced by [[Participant (company)|Participant Media]] along with [[Mark Ruffalo]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|title='Carol' Helmer Todd Haynes To Direct 'Dry Run' Drama For Participant Media|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144115/https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> In November 2018, Ruffalo was officially set to star in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|title=Mark Ruffalo To Star In Participant Media's Todd Haynes Pic About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=November 9, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144302/https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Christine Vachon]] and Pamela Koffler producing under their [[Killer Films]] banner.<ref name=\"MoreCast\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144355/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] began on January 14, 2019, in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"MoreCast\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|title=Shooting for film starring Mark Ruffalo, Anne Hathaway begins in Hamilton Monday|last=\"WKRC\"|date=January 11, 2019|website=Local12.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144422/https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released in limited theatres on November 22, 2019, before going wide on December 6, 2019.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|title=\u2018Dark Waters\u2019 Leads Tepid Arthouse Openers at Crowded Box Office|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=November 27, 2019|website=[[Indiewire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144435/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Dark Waters'' grossed $11.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $9.9 million in other countries, for a worldwide total of $21 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nIn its opening weekend the film made $102,656 from four theaters, a per-venue average of $25,651.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> It expanded to 94 theaters the following weekend, making $630,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|title='Harriet,' 'Jojo Rabbit,' and 'Parasite' Reap Holiday Box Office Bounty|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=December 1, 2019|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144741/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref> The film went wide in its third weekend of release, making $4.1 million from 2,012 theaters, and then made $1.9 million in its fourth weekend.<ref name=\"expand\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|title=\u2018Frozen 2\u2019 Leads Dreary December Weekend With $34M+, \u2018Playmobil\u2019 Plunges To $670K \u2013 Sunday Update|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 8, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144822/https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|title=\u2018Jumanji: The Next Level\u2019 Advancing To $51M+ Opening; \u2018Richard Jewell\u2019 & \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 Earn Lumps Of Coal|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 15, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144821/https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 90% based on 197 reviews, with an average rating of 7.3/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Dark Waters'' powerfully relays a real-life tale of infuriating malfeasance, honoring the victims and laying blame squarely at the feet of the perpetrators.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019/|title=Dark Waters (2019)|date=December 6, 2019|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144827/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 72 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|title=Dark Waters Reviews|date=November 22, 2019|website=Metacritic|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145211/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars, with 60% saying they would definitely recommend it to a friend.<ref name=expand/>\n\n=== Economic response ===\nThe DowDuPont breakup earlier in the year spun off a new DuPont company that continued to lose value throughout the second half of 2019 as investors grew concerned about the potential liabilities related to the old DuPont's fluoropolymer products. When ''Dark Waters'' was released on November 12, DuPont's stock price dropped even further by 7.15 points from 72.18 to 65.03. While the portfolio is now a part of [[Chemours]] and the companies settled the public health lawsuits referenced in the film, Chemours sued DuPont, alleging that the former parent company saddled it with onerous liabilities when it failed to prepare financial projections in good faith. Chemours estimated that it would need to pay over $200 million to address environmental damages in North Carolina caused by another PFAS manufacturing facility in that region. (The prior settlement in both West Virginia and Ohio cost $671 million, which was split between the two companies.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|title=Here's Why DuPont Fell 40.5% in 2019|last=Chatsko|first=Maxx|date=January 9, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145208/https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuPont CEO Marc Doyle, executives, and investors argued in internal statements that much of the movie was not based in fact and DuPont was misconstrued to fit the role of the enemy. According to Doyle, limited public statements were made because \u201cin a situation like this, it just doesn\u2019t do you much good to fight it out in the public eye. That would just drive more and more attention to it.\u201d Executive chairman Ed Breen wouldn\u2019t comment on whether DuPont would take legal action in response to the movie, but he did tell investors, \u201cObviously, we have a lot of legal folks [that] have been looking at this.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|title=DuPont execs react to villain role in \u2018Dark Waters\u2019 film|last=Eichmann|first=Mark|date=November 1, 2019|website=whyy.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145229/https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Many of the executives with whom this movie draws fault still work, or recently worked at DuPont. 3M saw little to no change in its stock price the day of the film's release, but it was already experiencing a \"difficult year\" from \"potential liabilities due to possible litigation over previous production of PFAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|title=Is 3M Stock a Buy for 2020? The industrial giant had a very difficult 2019, but is it set for a turnaround in the coming year?|last=Samaha|first=Lee|date=December 18, 2019|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145533/https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> 3M's stock price closed at 256.01 on January 28, 2018, and by December 1, 2019, it had fallen to 168.27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|title=News & Analysis: 3M|last=Nyitray|first=Brent|date=April 1, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145639/https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Satellite Awards]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[24th Satellite Awards|December 19, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor, Drama]]\n| [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|title=24th Satellite Awards nominations|date=2019|website=pressacademy.com|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145910/https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Mario Correa, [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], Nathaniel Rich\n| {{nom}}\n |-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cinema for Peace]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala|February 23, 2020\n| Award for Justice 2020\n| ''Dark Waters''\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n|-\n| International Green Film Award 2020\n| ''Dark Waters''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Perfluorinated alkylated substances]] (PFAS)\n* [[Timeline of events related to per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)]]\n* ''[[The Devil We Know]]'' (2018 investigative documentary)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Todd Haynes}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2010s legal films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films about lawyers]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Todd Haynes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Christine Vachon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Films set in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2000]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2004]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2009]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2010]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2011]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Killer Films films]]\n", "name_user": "Cocap31", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Waters_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "Canadian federal election results in the C\u00f4te-Nord and Saguenay", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Canadian federal election results\n| year1 = [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019]]\n| party1a = BQ\n| seats1a = 4\n| party1b = Conservative\n| seats1b = 1\n| year2 = 2015\n| party2b = NDP\n| seats2b = 1\n| party2d = Conservative\n| seats2d = 2\n| party2c = Liberal\n| seats2c = 1\n| party2a = BQ\n| seats2a = 1\n| year3 = 2011\n| party3a = NDP\n| seats3a = 4\n| party3b = Conservative\n| seats3b = 1\n| year4 = 2008\n| party4a = BQ\n| seats4a = 3\n| party4b = Conservative\n| seats4b = 2\n| year5 = 2006\n| party5a = BQ\n| seats5a = 4\n| party5b = Conservative\n| seats5b = 1\n| year6 = 2004\n| party6a = BQ\n| seats6a = 5\n| year7 = 2000\n| party7a = BQ\n| seats7a = 6\n| party7b = Liberal\n| seats7b = 1\n| year8 = [[1997 Canadian federal election|1997]]\n| party8a = BQ\n| seats8a = 6\n| party8b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats8b = 1\n| year9 = [[1993 Canadian federal election|1993]]\n| party9a = BQ\n| seats9a = 7\n| year10 = [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988]]\n| party10a = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats10a = 7\n| year11 = [[1984 Canadian federal election|1984]]\n| party11a = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats11a = 7\n| year12 = [[1980 Canadian federal election|1980]]\n| party12a = Liberal\n| seats12a = 7\n| year13 = [[1979 Canadian federal election|1979]]\n| party13a = Liberal\n| seats13a = 6\n| party13b = Social Credit\n| seats13b = 1\n| year14 = [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974]]\n| party14a = Liberal\n| seats14a = 6\n| party14b = Social Credit\n| seats14b = 1\n| year15 = [[1972 Canadian federal election|1972]]\n| party15a = Liberal\n| seats15a = 5\n| party15b = Social Credit\n| seats15b = 2\n| year16 = [[1968 Canadian federal election|1968]]\n| party16a = Liberal\n| seats16a = 5\n| party16c = Social Credit\n| seats16c = 1\n| party16b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats16b = 1\n| year17 = [[1965 Canadian federal election|1965]]\n| party17a = Liberal\n| seats17a = 2\n| party17c = Social Credit\n| seats17c = 3\n| party17b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats17b = 1\n| year18 = [[1963 Canadian federal election|1963]]\n| party18a = Liberal\n| seats18a = 1\n| party18b = Social Credit\n| seats18b = 5\n| year19 = [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962]]\n| party19a = Social Credit\n| seats19a = 6\n| year20 = [[1958 Canadian federal election|1958]]\n| party20a = Liberal\n| seats20a = 1\n| party20b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats20b = 5\n| year21 = [[1957 Canadian federal election|1957]]\n| party21a = Liberal\n| seats21a = 6\n| year22 = [[1953 Canadian federal election|1953]]\n| party22a = Liberal\n| seats22a = 4\n| party22b = Independent \n| seats22b = 2\n}}\n\n'''Canadian federal elections''' have provided the following '''results''' in '''the C\u00f4te-Nord and Saguenay'''.\n\n==Regional Profile==\nThis region used to be traditionally [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]], except for Roberval which has voted for the Social Credit Party. The Liberal dominance ended in [[1984 Canadian federal election|1984]] as [[Brian Mulroney]], who is from this area, was able to gather Quebec nationalist support and sweep the region in 1984 and [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988]]. With the advent of the nationalist [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] in 1993, nationalist support left the Tories, and this area became a traditional Bloc stronghold. This is true except for the [[Chicoutimi, Quebec|Chicoutimi]] area which has voted federalist with [[Andr\u00e9 Harvey]] running as a [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] and winning in 1997, and running as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] and winning in 2000. The Bloc swept the region in 2004, but the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] picked up a seat here in [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006]] and weakened the Bloc's grip on the remaining seats as Liberal support collapsed. In 2011, another regional sweep gave four of the five seats to the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democrats]], shutting out the Bloc and leaving the Conservatives with one of their two seats. In the 2015 election, the NDP lost all but one of its seat in the region, while the Bloc managed a comeback in the C\u00f4te-Nord region, the Liberals won one seat in Chicoutimi and the Conservatives won one seat in the southwestern part of the region near Quebec City.\n\n=== Votes by party throughout time ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Evolution of party standings throughout time\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\"|Party\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1988\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1993\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1997\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2000\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2004\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2006\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2008\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2011\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2015\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2019\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n|-\n| {{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|background}}|\n| |{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|name}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|48,609\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|17.9%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|41,916\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|15.5%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|59,370\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|23.3%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|85,687\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|35.5%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|57,501\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|28.7%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|28,348\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12.7%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|23,249\n| style=\"text